ProMED-PORT

[We are told in the news reports above of a cluster of 5 (or perhaps 6) confirmed cases of invasive meningococcal disease (i.e., meningococcal meningitis and/or meningococcemia) caused by serogroup C reported in the same section of the city of São Paulo in the past 2 months. However, we are not told the ages of all cases, their meningococcal vaccination status, if the cases belonged to certain high-risk groups, such as university students living in dormitories or men who have sex with men, had close contact with someone belonging to a high-risk group, or had some other epidemiological link. Also, has there been molecular typing of the meningococcal strains to demonstrate if they are genetically linked?

In the United States, 95% of cases of invasive meningococcal disease are sporadic, each case unrelated to the other cases; meningococcal outbreaks account for only about 5% of reported cases. The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends:

"All cases of meningococcal disease of the same serogroup should be included in the outbreak case count unless molecular typing indicates that the strain from a case is genetically different than the predominant outbreak strain. In outbreaks with well-defined risk groups, probable cases may be included as outbreak associated even if they are unable to be confirmed or serogrouped.

"The outbreak threshold for vaccine decision-making should be determined on a case-by-case basis, using the following general guidance:
- Organization-based outbreak: 2-3 outbreak-associated cases within an organization during a 3-month period
- Community-based outbreak: multiple outbreak-associated cases with an incidence of meningococcal disease that is above the expected incidence in a community during a 3-month period"
(https://www.cdc.gov/meningococcal/downloads/meningococcal-outbreak-guidance.pdf)

Clusters of invasive meningococcal disease have been reported in cities in North America, Europe, and Australia among men who have sex with men (MSM), associated with a high case-fatality rate. All cases were caused by hypervirulent serogroup C strains of _Neisseria meningitidis_ (MenC) belonging to the sequence type (ST) 11. (Please see ProMED post Meningitis, meningococcal - USA (08): (FL) fatal, more cases, 17 counties 20220914.8705585.)

Vila Formosa (pop., 94 799 residents in 2007) is one of the 96 districts in the city of São Paulo, Brazil, located in the east side of the city about 4 km [2.5 mi] from Aricanduva (pop., 94 130 in 2008) (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vila_Formosa and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aricanduva_(district_of_São_Paulo)). The 2 neighborhoods can be found on a map of Sao Paulo at https://www.google.com/maps/dir/Vila+Formosa,+São+Paulo+-+State+of+São+Paulo,+Brazil/Aricanduva,+São+Paulo+-+State+of+São+Paulo,+03906-060,+Brazil/.

More information from knowledgeable sources concerning these cases of invasive meningococcal disease in Sao Paulo would be appreciated. - Mod.ML

